s Name] provides [specific service] for [target customer] \nin [city/area]. Our [service] includes [specific details of what's included]. \n[Outcome statement]. [Credential or trust signal]. Serving [neighborhoods/areas].\nPrice: [Range or \"Contact for quote\"]\n```\n\n### Scoring (0-10)\n- 0: No custom services\n- 3: Generic keyword-only services\n- 5: Some detailed, some generic\n- 7: All services detailed with descriptions\n- 10: Every service is a micro-landing page targeting high-intent long-tails\n\n---\n\n## SPEC-002: GBP DESCRIPTION ENGINEERING\n\n### Core Concept ‚Äî The \"Local Hub Gambit\"\nThe 750-character GBP description uses entity co-citations to signal that the business is a connected local hub, not an isolated listing. Mentioning verifiable local entities (suppliers, associations, landmarks, builders) creates semantic relationships that Google validates.\n\n### Structure (750 characters max)\n```\n[Opening identity statement with primary keyword + city]\n[Entity co-citation #1 ‚Äî local supplier, partner, or association]\n[Entity co-citation #2 ‚Äî landmark, neighborhood, or institution]\n[Core services with specific details]\n[Credential/trust signals ‚Äî years, certifications, awards]\n[Service area with specific neighborhoods]\n[Closing CTA]\n```\n\n### Entity Co-Citation Categories\n- **Suppliers/Partners:** Local suppliers the business actually uses (verifiable)\n- **Professional Associations:** Chamber of Commerce, industry groups, BBB\n- **Geographic Anchors:** Landmarks, neighborhoods, shopping centers, highways\n- **Complementary Businesses:** Other local businesses that serve same customers\n\n### Rules\n- Every entity mentioned MUST be real and verifiable by Google\n- Never fabricate relationships ‚Äî Google cross-checks\n- Front-load the primary keyword + city in the first sentence\n- No phone numbers, URLs, or promotional language in description\n- Write in third person (\"Business Name provides...\" not \"We provide...\")\n\n### Scoring (0-10)\n- 0: Empty or auto-generated\n- 3: Basic description, no entity co-citations\n- 5: Keyword-optimized but missing authority signals\n- 7: Entity co-citations + credentials + geo-modifiers\n- 10: Full Local Hub Gambit with 3+ verifiable entity co-citations\n\n---\n\n## SPEC-003: GBP Q&A PRE-EMPTION\n\n### Core Concept\nSeed 15-30 Q&A entries before customers ask random questions. Each answer is a keyword-dense content block that Google indexes and uses for relevance signals.\n\n### Procedure\n1. Generate questions from keyword research (what people actually search)\n2. Write comprehensive answers (150-500 characters each)\n3. Post questions from a Google account, then answer as the business owner\n4. Include natural keyword variations in answers\n5. For complex topics, link to a Google Doc \"answer funnel\" (public doc with detailed guide)\n\n### Question Categories\n- **Service-specific:** \"Do you offer [specific service] in [city]?\"\n- **Pricing:** \"How much does [service] cost?\"\n- **Process:** \"What's the process for [service]?\"\n- **Credentials:** \"Are you licensed/insured/certified for [service]?\"\n- **Area:** \"Do you serve [neighborhood/city]?\"\n- **Comparison:** \"What's the difference between [option A] and [option B]?\"\n\n### Answer Template\n```\nQ: [Question matching a real search query]\nA: Yes, [Business Name] offers [service] in [city/area]. [2-3 sentences with \nspecific details ‚Äî pricing, process, timeline, or qualifications]. \n[For more details: link to Google Doc guide if applicable]. \nContact us at [phone] to [CTA].\n```\n\n### Google Docs Answer Funnel\nFor complex questions that exceed Q&A character limits:\n1. Create a comprehensive Google Doc (2,000+ words, publicly viewable)\n2. Link from Q&A answer: \"We created a free guide: [Doc link]\"\n3. This creates a Google-to-Google trust signal (GBP ‚Üí Google Docs)\n\n### Scoring (0-10)\n- 0: No Q&A entries\n- 3: Few generic Q&A, thin answers\n- 5: 10-15 entries, moderate keyword density\n- 7: 20+ entries, comprehensive answers, all service areas covered\n- 10: 30+ entries with answer funnels, covering every service + area + FAQ\n\n---\n\n## SPEC-004: GBP PRODUCTS TAB\n\n### Core Concept\nProducts tab is a visual conversion tool. Each product entry has an image, description, price, and CTA button ‚Äî functioning as a visual menu of offerings.\n\n### Procedure\n1. Create product collections (categories) matching service categories\n2. For each product/service:\n   - Professional image (real photos preferred over stock)\n   - Descriptive title (service name, not generic)\n   - Detailed description (features, benefits, what's included)\n   - Price or price range\n   - CTA button (Call, Learn More, Book)\n3. Prioritize highest-margin or most-searched services first\n\n### Template\n```\nCollection: [Service Category]\nProduct Name: [Specific Service Name]\nDescription: [What it includes, who it's for, key benefit, timeframe]\nPrice: $X,XXX or $X,XXX - $X,XXX or \"Request Quote\"\nCTA: [Call / Learn More / Book Online]\nImage: [Professional photo of this service in action]\n```\n\n### Scoring (0-10)\n- 0: Products tab empty\n- 3: Few products, no images or descriptions\n- 5: Products listed but generic descriptions\n- 7: All services as products with images and descriptions\n- 10: Complete product catalog with professional images, pricing, compelling descriptions\n\n---\n\n## SPEC-005: GBP POSTING STRATEGY\n\n### Core Concept ‚Äî Pre-Emptive Framing\nPosts seed content into Google's index and AI systems. The strategy isn't promotional ‚Äî it's about framing the business as the authority in its market by defining what quality means, then demonstrating the business meets those criteria.\n\n### Cadence\n3 posts per week minimum. Schedule:\n- **Monday:** Service/expertise highlight\n- **Wednesday:** Community/local engagement\n- **Friday:** Offer, event, or seasonal content\n\n### Post Types & Templates\n**Service Highlight:**\n```\n[Service Name] in [City] ‚Äî What to Know in [Year]\n\n[2-3 sentences positioning the business as expert on this service. \nInclude specific details: pricing, process, timeline.]\n\n[Credential or trust signal.]\n\nüìû [Phone] | üåê [Website]\n```\n\n**Pre-Emptive Framing Post:**\n```\nWhen choosing a [service provider] in [city], look for:\n‚úÖ [Credential your client has]\n‚úÖ [Feature your client offers]\n‚úÖ [Trust signal your client possesses]\n\n[Business Name] meets all three ‚Äî [brief proof statement].\n```\n\n**Community Post:**\n```\n[Business Name] is proud to [support/partner with/attend] [local event/organization].\n[1-2 sentences about the connection.]\n[Tag or mention the local entity for co-citation.]\n```\n\n### Rules\n- Every post must include a CTA (call, visit, book)\n- Include at least one geo-modifier per post\n- Vary keywords across posts (don't repeat the same keyword every post)\n- Include a photo with every post (real > stock)\n- Never use GBP posts for link building or thin content\n\n### Scoring (0-10)\n- 0: No posts or last post > 30 days ago\n- 3: Sporadic posting, generic content\n- 5: 1-2 posts/week, some keyword optimization\n- 7: 3/week, pre-emptive framing, local entity mentions\n- 10: 3+/week, full framing strategy, consistent for 3+ months\n\n---\n\n## ROUTE 1 EXECUTION CHECKLIST\n\nWhen auditing a client's GBP:\n```\n‚òê Score each of the 5 areas (SPEC-001‚Äì005)\n‚òê Identify lowest-scoring area ‚Üí highest priority\n‚òê Generate deliverables for all areas scoring < 7\n‚òê Present to operator as a GBP optimization package:\n  - Rewritten description (ready to paste)\n  - Expanded services list (ready to add)\n  - Q&A entries (ready to post)\n  - Product entries (ready to create)\n  - First 2 weeks of posts (ready to schedule)\n```\n[/DOC]\n\n--- END AWARENESS ---"
